# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: adamorobe-sign-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The capital's architecture reflects this history, ranging from 19th-century colonial architecture to modern skyscrapers and apartment blocks.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Accra is the Greater Accra Region's economic and administrative hub, and serves as the anchor of the larger Greater Accra Metropolitan Area (GAMA), which is inhabited by about 4 million people, making it the thirteenth-largest metropolitan area in Africa.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] In 2020, the Globalization and World Cities Research Network think tank designated Accra as a "Gamma −" level global city, indicating a growing level of international influence and connectedness.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The word *Accra* is derived from the Akan word *Nkran* meaning "ants", a reference to anthills seen in the countryside around Accra.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The name specifically refers to soldier ants, and was applied to the town and people by the Twi speakers.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The name of Accra in the local Ga language is *Ga* or *Gaga*, the same name as that of the Ga people and a cognate with *Nkran*.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The word is sometimes rendered with the nasalised vowels as *Gã* or *Gãgã*.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Historian Carl Christian Reindorf confirmed this etymology, proposing a link between the martial qualities and migratory behaviour of the local ants and those of the Ga people.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The link between the ethnonym and ants was explicitly reflected in the recognition of anthills as sacred places.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Sometimes ringed by sacred fences (*aklabatsa*), the tall red mounds dotting Accra's hinterland were seen as microcosms of human community and as nodal points between the known world and the world of the dead.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The Gas used the reference to the invasive species of dark-red swarming ants to connote the military prowess of the Gas and their ancient conquest of Guang speakers residing in the Accra Plains.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The name *Ga* is actually a cognate of the name *Akan*, one of the words in which [g] corresponds to [k] in Akan.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] *Ga* also gave its name to the Ga districts surrounding Accra.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The spelling *Accra* was given to *Nkran* by Europeans.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] By the 15th century, the kingdom of Accra ruled the area from the capital at Ayawaso.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Initially, Accra was not the most prominent trading centre; the trading hubs were the ports at Ada and Prampram, along with the inland centres of Dodowa and Akuse.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] A Portuguese fort was destroyed by the local inhabitants in 1576; trade afterwards was conducted on the beaches.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The Dutch later built the nearby Fort Crèvecœur while the British and the Swedes built James Fort and Christiansborg castles, respectively, in the 17th century.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] By 1646 the kingdom was a regional power, bolstered by European trade.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] It depended on the goodwill of the rising Akwamu Kingdom, which controlled the trade routes in the interior.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] A dispute in 1646 escalated to war when Accra invaded Larteh.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] At the same time, Accra was weakened by a civil war.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] In 1677 Akwamuhene Ansa Sasraku, using the circumcision of a visiting Akwamu prince as pretext, attacked Accra.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] He sacked Ayawaso and beheaded the king, Okai Koi.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The king's son, Ofori, retreated to 'Small Accra', the town that had grown up under the walls of Fort Crèvecœur.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Ansa Sasraku's attempts to finish off the Accrans were defeated by the guns of the Danish Fort Christianborg.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Ofori and his people survived for years, until the Akwamu fomented a rebellion amongst the Danish garrison, and the fort was turned over to the Portuguese.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Ansa Sasraku returned in 1681, burning Osu town and Small Accra and chasing Ofori to exile in Fetu.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] As Akwamu continued to expand, strips of land east and west were added to the Accra province.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Britain gradually acquired the interests of all other countries beginning in 1851, when Denmark sold Christiansborg (which they had acquired from the Swedes) and their other forts to the British.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The Netherlands was the last to sell out, in 1871.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] In 1873, after decades of tension between the British and Ashantis, the British captured Kumasi, destroying portions of the city.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The British then captured Accra in 1874, and in 1877, at the end of the second Anglo-Asante War, Accra replaced Cape Coast as the capital of the British Gold Coast.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] This decision was made because Accra had a drier climate relative to Cape Coast.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Until this time, the settlement of Accra was confined between Ussher Fort to the east and the Korle Lagoon to the west.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Victoriaborg was formed in the 19th century as an exclusively European residential neighbourhood, located to the east of the city limits of the time.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The boundaries of Accra were further stretched in 1908, after a bubonic plague epidemic.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] This expansion entailed the creation of a native-only neighbourhood, intended to accommodate members of the native population as a means of relieving congestion problems in the overcrowded city centre.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Adabraka was thus established to the north of the city.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] In 1918, the Grand Orange Lodge of Ghana was established in Accra to oversee and govern the local Ghanaian Orange Lodges.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The Ghanaian Orange Order focus on evangelism, positive values and youth development.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] They have Orange parades in the city, such as the 12th of July parade.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] By the 1920s, transportation between Accra and the inland cities producing exportable commodities was enhanced.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] This allowed cocoa to become Accra's largest export and allowed commerce to overtake government as the primary element in the city.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Among the achievements of Guggisberg was the building of a bridge across the Korle Lagoon in 1923, which increased settlement at Korle Bu, Korle Gonno and Chokor, to the west of the lagoon.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Guggisberg also oversaw the building of a hospital (Korle-Bu) and secondary school (Achimota).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] In 1948, Ghana remained a colony of Great Britain following World War II.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The chief of Osu Alata, Nii Kobina Bonney III, had set up a boycott of European goods across the country due to the rise of prices for essential commodities.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] At the same time, veterans of the war were fighting for their benefits and promised pay.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] After Kwame Nkrumah became Ghana's first Prime Minister in 1957, he created his own plan for Accra's development.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Nkrumah proposed creating spaces to inspire pride and nationalism in his people and people throughout Africa.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The Parliament, Supreme Court of Ghana, Black Star Square and the Bank of Ghana are located in Accra.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The city is a transportation hub, home to Accra International Airport, and railway links to Tema, Sekondi-Takoradi and Kumasi.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Accra has become a location for national and international business conferences, such as the BarCamp Ghana series, organised by GhanaThink Foundation.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] As a coastal city, Accra is vulnerable to the impacts of climate change and sea level rise, with population growth putting increasing pressure on the coastal areas.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Drainage infrastructure is particularly at risk, which has implications for people's livelihoods, especially in informal settlements.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The administration of Accra occurs at two levels.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Strategic initiatives, such as the urban transportation project, are coordinated between district authorities.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Geographically, the areas west of Ring Road West, extending as far west as the saltponds and south of Graphic Road, are considered Accra West.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The period between 1960 and 1970 saw more rapid industrialization and expansion in Accra's manufacturing and commercial sectors.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] This contributed to higher rural-urban migration to the city, and consequently a higher population growth rate.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] 56% of the population of Accra is under 24 years of age.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] 51% of the population are females, and the remaining 49% males.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] This gives a males-to-females ratio of 1:1.04.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The greater number of females is a reflection of the nationwide trend, where the estimated ratio of males to females is 1:1.03.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] In 2008, the World Bank estimated that Accra's economy constituted around US$3 billion of Ghana's total gross domestic product (GDP).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Accra is a centre for manufacturing, marketing, finance, insurance, and transportation.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The road network in the Accra Metropolitan Area totals 1,117 kilometres (694 mi) in length.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] There are over 50,506 identified residential properties in Accra, and about 4,054 commercial/industrial/mixed properties, with a total rateable value of GH¢13,849,014.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The tertiary service sector is the city's largest, employing about 531,670 people.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The second-largest, the secondary sector, employs 22.34% of the labour force, or around 183,934 people.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] 12.2% of the city's workforce are reportedly unemployed, totalling around 114,198 people.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Pre-school comprises nursery and kindergarten.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] In 2001, there were 7,923 children (3,893 girls and 4,030 boys) in pre-schools in Accra.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] In 2010, the enrolment rate at Pre-school was 98%.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Primary school enrolment of girls is higher than that of boys.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] In 2010, the enrollment rate at primary school level was 95%.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] In 2010, the enrolment rate at Junior high school level was 95%.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The ratio of girls is higher at this level.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The transition rate between junior high and senior high school increased from 30% in 1990 to 50% in 2001.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The number of students grew by 23,102 between 1990 and 2005, an increase of about 2,310 a year, since 2010 the senior high school enrolment rate has been 95%.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Ghana International School (GIS), a private non-profit A-Level school founded in 1955 for children from ages 3–18, is located in Accra's Cantonments.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Abelemkpe is the home of Lincoln Community School, a private, non-profit International Baccalaureate (IB) school for students aged 3–18, established in 1968.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Mary's Senior High School, also referred to as "Merriez", is a girls' boarding school in Ghana; St.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The University of Ghana is located 13 kilometres (8.1 mi) north of the city centre at Legon.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] A number of other public and private universities and tertiary institutions have since been founded in Accra, some of which are listed below.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] As a growing city, Accra has a water supply and scarcity challenge.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Water access uses a patchwork of different delivery processes.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Accra as a growing city, with vehicles and other urban pollution sources, has an increasing amount of air pollution and plastic pollution.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Accra's urban ecosystem has been a site of dumping by international waste networks, with the Agbogbloshie suburb known for its e-waste recycling sites, and the Kantamanto Market as handling an overwhelming flow of used fast fashion from other parts of the world.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Both sites are sources of pollution and trash for other parts of the urban ecosystem.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Air pollution varies seasonally, and the average measure PM2.5 average concentration of 49.5 μg/m3.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Live monitoring of air pollution is done at three sites in the city of Accra.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] A 2021 review by the Environmental Protection Agency in Ghana found that the levels were exceeding national and international standards for health.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Plastic management is also an increasing challenge.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Use of plastic water bottles water sachets and other packaging for food safety, and use of plastic during events like COVID-19 have increased plastic pollution.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The beaches around Accra have plastic pollution, and surrounding fisheries are impacted by plastics.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Non-profit organizations have been formed to collect the plastic and an increasingly growing network of recyclers and informal waste recovery networks.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Activists and researchers largely attribute the issue to upstream use of plastics.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] There's been decongestion exercises carried out by successive mayors in the city to help solve the hawking menace, flood issues and ensure road safety in the city.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Growing population and construction within the city has been resulting in a reduction in Urban green space.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] A 2021 study of low income communities in the city found increasing concern and desire among these communities for urban green spaces for recreation and health.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] A 2018 study of greenspaces in the city, found the ones that do exist are important for mammal biodiversity in the city.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Accra is on the Atlantic coast and has not served as a port city since the 1950s.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Instead, the Port of Tema, about 29 km to the east along the Atlantic coast, was developed for deepwater shipping to and from Ghana as it can accommodate larger ships; the port opened in 1961.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Accra is connected by railway line to Kumasi and Takoradi.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] There is a suburban railway line from Accra Central Station to Tema.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Accra is served by Accra International Airport, which has civil and military uses.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Located 6 miles (9.7 kilometres) from downtown Accra, the airport handles all of the city's scheduled passenger services.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] There are plans to build a second airport to relieve the aviation pressure on the Accra International Airport.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] This new airport will be located at Prampram in Accra and will be constructed by China Airport Civil Construction.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] This plan was still under review in 2020, as additional runways at Kotoka are in consideration as an alternative to a new international airport.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Accra has a taxi network and taxi ranks, and most taxis lack a meter system, so price negotiation is required between the passenger and driver.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Metered taxis operate in the city, and tend to be more expensive.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Taxis in Ghana are painted in two colours: the four bumpers fenders are yellow/orange, and the rest of the car is in a colour of the operator's choice.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] These taxis usually function on a shared ride model, where several passengers share one vehicle and the fare is calculated based on the distance traveled.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] More modern taxi services such as Uber, Taxify, and Yango have joined the market, providing a more advanced and comfortable alternative.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Some taxi drivers might charge extra for luggage or late-night trips while some also offer fixed prices and allow for advance bookings, offering a more reliable and secure option.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Tourism in Ghana accounted for 1,087,000 international tourist arrivals in 2011.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Accra is the Greater Accra region's tourist hub, sporting hotels, monuments, museums and nightclubs.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The city has three five-star hotels: the Labadi Beach Hotel, the La Palm Royal Beach Hotel and the Movenpick Ambassador Hotel.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The Golden Tulip Hotel and Novotel Accra, located in Accra's central business district, are ranked four stars.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] There are three-star hotels, including the Hotel Wangara, Hotel Shangri-La and Erata Hotel, and budget hotels.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] The Accra International Conference Centre and other meeting facilities provide venues for conference tourism.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] In 1994, Emmanuel Aboki Essien, a high-up member within the Grand Orange Lodge of Ghana, in Accra, was elected President of the Imperial Orange Council, the governing body of the worldwide Orange Order.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] He was the first African to hold this position, raising the profile of African Orange lodges within the fraternity.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Accra hold orange walks to celebrate historical events, such as the Battle of the Boyne.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] Its first documentary addressing the impacts of climate change premiered in Accra on 14 October 2022.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/accra] In October 2022, Accra was named by the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) as World Book Capital for 2023.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] For over a decade, the deaf children of the village have attended a boarding school in Mampong-Akuapem, where the ASL based Ghanaian Sign Language is used.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] As a consequence, this language has become the first language of these children and their command of AdaSL is decreasing.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] This is likely to lead to a complete shift of the deaf community in Adamorobe to Ghanaian Sign Language.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] As such, AdaSL is an endangered sign language.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Adamorobe is situated approximately 30 to 40 kilometers north of Accra in the Akuapem Hills.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] It is a predominantly Akan village, with the majority of the population speaking the Akan language (Akuapem Twi) in addition to using AdaSL.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The community gained attention for its unusually high incidence of hereditary deafness, a phenomenon that has shaped the village's cultural and linguistic landscape.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many other deaf communities where deaf individuals are socially marginalized, Adamorobe's deaf residents are fully integrated into village life.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Hearing villagers commonly use AdaSL in daily interactions, creating a bilingual environment that bridges the hearing and deaf worlds seamlessly.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL shares signs and prosodic features with some other sign languages in the region, such as Bura Sign Language, but it has been suggested these similarities are due to culturally shared gestures rather than a genetic relationship.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL has features that set it apart from the sign languages of large deaf communities studied so far, including the absence of the type of classifier construction that expresses motion or location (sometimes called "entity classifiers").
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Instead, AdaSL uses several types of serial verb constructions also found in the surrounding spoken language, Akan.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Nancy Frishberg suggests that AdaSL may be related to the "gestural trade jargon used in the markets throughout West Africa".
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Adamorobe Sign Language possesses distinct grammatical structures and vocabulary that set it apart from Ghanaian Sign Language and other national or international sign languages.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many urban sign languages that develop within educational institutions, AdaSL evolved organically within a close-knit community, resulting in unique syntactic constructions and simultaneous sign formations.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Its use is characterized by spatial grammar, classifier constructions, and gestures deeply embedded in the local culture.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The language is not mutually intelligible with GSL, and many signs are specific to Adamorobe's cultural context, making it a rich subject of linguistic study.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL also exhibits a lower reliance on fingerspelling compared to GSL, and it preserves several features that are considered archaic or absent in more standardized sign languages.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Deaf culture in Adamorobe is notably inclusive.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Deaf residents have historically participated fully in social, economic, and cultural activities.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many other societies, deafness in Adamorobe does not carry a stigma.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Instead, sign language has been a natural and respected form of communication, used not only by deaf individuals but also by hearing family members, friends, and neighbors.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] This integration is evident in communal gatherings, marketplaces, and traditional ceremonies where sign language is used openly.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The social fabric of Adamorobe has long celebrated this coexistence, which has contributed to the resilience of its deaf community despite external pressures.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL is believed to have emerged over 200 years ago, alongside the settlement's founding.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Genetic studies suggest that the high incidence of deafness in Adamorobe is due to a hereditary mutation passed down through generations.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The earliest academic references to Adamorobe and its sign language date back to the mid-20th century, with researchers noting the community's unique integration of deaf individuals.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] In the 1960s and 1980s, the introduction of formal deaf education in Ghana led to the exposure of Adamorobe's deaf children to Ghanaian Sign Language, which is derived from American Sign Language (ASL).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] This exposure began to shift the linguistic practices of younger generations, who now tend to use GSL more frequently than AdaSL.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] A critical turning point in the village's history came in 1975 when the local chief instituted a ban on marriages between deaf individuals in an effort to reduce the incidence of hereditary deafness.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] While this policy effectively decreased the number of deaf births, it also inadvertently threatened the long-term survival of AdaSL.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Today, Adamorobe Sign Language faces significant challenges.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The number of deaf individuals in the village has declined due to the marriage policy that discouraged unions between deaf people.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Additionally, the younger generation of deaf children is increasingly adopting Ghanaian Sign Language through formal education, which reduces the intergenerational transmission of AdaSL.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The influence of urbanization and national language policies further accelerates the shift away from village sign languages.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Without deliberate preservation efforts, AdaSL risks becoming endangered or possibly extinct within the next few decades.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Several linguists and anthropologists have documented Adamorobe Sign Language extensively in recent years.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Their efforts aim to preserve the language's unique features and raise awareness of its cultural importance.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] However, there are limited formal initiatives within the village to revitalize or maintain AdaSL among younger generations.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Potential preservation strategies include community-based language programs, the development of AdaSL teaching materials, and the integration of the language into local schools.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Encouraging the use of AdaSL in social and cultural events could also contribute to its sustainability.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Education for the deaf in Afghanistan grew out of educational efforts among Afghan refugees in Peshawar in the 1990s, making Pakistani Sign Language (IPSL) an early influence on Afghan Sign Language.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] The first formal school for the deaf in Afghanistan was established in Jalalabad in 1995 by SERVE Afghanistan.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] That same year, SERVE began a project to document Afghan Sign Language, and later produced a trilingual (Dari, Pashto, and English) dictionary of Afghan Sign Language.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] The language derives from the Deaf-community sign language of Jalalabad, and it is not known what connection it may have, if any, with the sign languages of other cities with established deaf populations, which are principally Mazar-i-Sharif, Herat, and Kandahar.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Early analysis suggested some AFSL signs may have come from Pakistani Sign Language (IPSL) or American Sign Language (ASL), although intensive research on this link was not undertaken at the time.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] While IPSL's influence would have been due to regional exchange, ASL could have had an influence due to its use by some SERVE teachers in its early programming.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Fingerspelling was introduced to AFSL in the late 1990s, after SERVE educators visited the Holy Land Institute for the Deaf in Jordan.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Thus, Jordanian Sign Language and AFSL share a fingerspelling alphabet, although AFSL also introduced some additional letters to represent letters not found in the Arabic script.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Afghan Sign Language is primarily spoken in Jalalabad and Kabul, which have three large schools for the deaf between them.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Smaller deaf populations who use AFSL are also found in major urban centers in the country, those being Mazar-e Sharif, Herat, and Kandahar.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] The majority of profoundly deaf Afghans (estimated at 30,000 in 2013) have never attended a school for the deaf.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The **Akan** (/ˈækæn/) people, or ***Akanfoɔ***, are a Kwa group living primarily in Ghana and parts of Ivory Coast in West Africa.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Akan speak languages within the Tano branch of the Niger–Congo family.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Subgroups of the Akan people include: the Adanse, Agona, Akuapem, Akwamu, Akyem, Anyi, Asante, Baoulé, Bono, Chakosi, Fante, Kwahu, Sefwi, Wassa, Ahanta, Denkyira and Nzema, among others.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Akan subgroups all have cultural attributes in common, most notably the tracing of royal matrilineal descent in the inheritance of property, and for succession to high political office.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] All Akans are considered royals in status, but not all are in royal succession or hold titles.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] According to **Jack Goody**, the origins of the Akan were distorted during the colonial period by misinterpretations popularized by missionaries, administrators, and early ethnographers.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] One of the earliest documented attempts to explain Akan origins was made by Thomas Edward Bowdich, an English traveler who visited the Asante Empire in 1817.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] He argued that there were similarities between Asante political institutions and those of Ancient Egypt and Ethiopia which indicated that the Asante descended from eastern or northeastern African populations.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Balmer, a missionary historian, advanced the view that the Akan originated from the medieval Ghana Empire in the western Sudan.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] He argued that the decline of ancient Ghana was due to the society losing internal cohesion and was weakened by Islam invasions into the Sahel.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Danquah later adopted and expanded the Ghana migration hypothesis using medieval Arabic descriptions of the ancient kingdom of Ghana and identifying it with the Akan-speaking peoples of the Gold Coast.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] In his 1944 book, the Akan Doctrine of God, Danquah suggested that the name “Ghana” represented an Arab corruption of “Akane” or “Akana,” and proposed a historical connection between the Akan and ancient Near Eastern civilizations.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Meyerowitz took the Ghana migration and diffusionist theories even further, claiming Akan ruling class and religious institutions originated from Saharan, Libyo-Berber, Egyptian, and Near Eastern sources.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The theories were criticized by historians, linguists, and anthropologists, who believed they served practical purposes for missionaries, colonial administrators, and nationalist thinkers who sought moral lessons, political unity, or historical prestige.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] An earlier critic of the colonial diffusionist theories was David Tait, who argued that Eva L.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Meyerowitz’s book of Akan origins relied too heavily on speculative links between names of peoples and places across separated regions.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] He criticized her attempt to connect the Akan, Guan and Gonja to the Fezzan and the Djenne–Timbuktu area, claiming that many of these links lacked clear evidence.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Tait denied to the use of a single Bono tradition about coming from the “great white desert” as the basis for a broad migration theory, especially since similar traditions were not found among other Akan groups.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] He also rejected the claim that early Bono traditions had been “lost,” arguing that there was no proof such traditions had ever existed.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] According to Tait, the linguistic comparisons used to support the argument crossed multiple languages and language families without enough methodological control.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] He believed that the book moved too quickly from collecting traditions to constructing speculative history, without first establishing the texts and their social context.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Dennis Michael Warren, an anthropologist who spent extended periods conducting fieldwork in Techiman, Ghana, reexamined Meyerowitz’s interpretations of Bono history and argued that they relied on unsupported evidence.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] According to his findings, many informants cited by Meyerowitz denied giving her the information associated with them or contradicted her statements when interviewed independently.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] His work exposed that Timbuktu, Kumbu, Diala, and Diadom were not commonly known in Bono oral tradition and were only recognized by people familiar with Meyerowitz’s ideas, suggesting that the narratives were introduced from herself and not passed down locally.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Warren concluded that an accurate reconstruction of Bono Manso history before the Asante conquest of 1722–1723 was not possible using available oral evidence.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Warren warned that Meyerowitz’s work had already entered school textbooks and popular histories as established fact and influence local narratives which made it difficult to distinguish authentic oral traditions from foreign fabrications.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] As more fieldwork was conducted in Akan regions, earlier statements associating Akan origins with migrations from different regions were questioned and reassessed.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Archaeologist Merrick Posnansky criticized the use of oral traditions recorded by non-specialists, arguing that the material, when interpreted through assumptions, created conflicting accounts of origins and lacked archaeological or historical validation.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Danquah and Eva Meyerowitz sought historical validated by projecting Near Eastern or Mesopotamian origins onto Akan societies.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] In 1995, following archaeological research, Peter and Ama Shinnie concluded that there is no evidence to support older theories proposing migrations of the Asante and other Akan peoples from North Africa, the Sahara, or the eastern Mediterranean.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] They argued the theories reflect outdated assumptions that complex societies in West Africa must have originated elsewhere rather than developing locally.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Oral traditions and archaeological evidence indicate that the Akan trace their origins to the forest and forest–savanna transition zone, with early settlements such of Bono Manso, Begho, Wenchi, Asantemanso and Adansemanso playing central roles in their historical development.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Bono people of Takyiman recount Bonoman one of the first Akan states, with its capital Bono Manso founded by a leader named Asaman, who emerged with his people from a sacred cave known as Amowi near modern day Techiman.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] According to tradition, God created the Bono before the sky itself, and their land was the birthplace of humankind.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The word “Bono” is said to mean “original” or “first.” Oral traditions from the Bono people of Old Wenchi recount that their ancestors first emerged from the ground at Bonoso, led out by a pig-like quadruped called *Wankyi*, before establishing their settlement at Old Wenchi (Ahwene Koko).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Bono people of the Nyarko, trace their ancestry to the ancestress Efua Nyarko, after whom a quarter of Begho was named.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] According to Adanse traditions and cosmogony, Adanse was the traditional “Garden of Eden” of all the Akan and is regarded as one of the first of the Akan states, standing at the head of the entire Akan nation.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] They recount that their land is considered a sacred place of creation and early political formation, regarded as the ancestral homeland from which all the southern Akan trace their origins.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] It is described as the first among five foundational states, Adanse, Akyem, Assin, Denkyira, and Asante, collectively called *Akanman Piesie Anum*.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Clans such as the Asona, Agona, Oyoko, and Bretuo are believed to have either originated from, settled, or have passed through Adanse.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Asante people trace their roots to Asantemanso, where the matriarch Ankyewa Nyame is said to have descended with sacred regalia, and where the founding clans emerged from the earth.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Akyem Kotoku, Akyem Bosome, Assin Atandansu, Assin Apimenin as well as the Asante of Mampong, Dwaben, Kokofu, among others, claim to have migrated at various times from the Adanse area of the Asante Region.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] These traditions emphasize sacred geography, clan emergence, and spiritual unity, with the deity Bona acting as guardian of Adanse's early cohesion.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Akwamu identify early capitals at Twifo-Hemang, Asamangkese and later Nyanaoase, located near key trade routes in the southern forests.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] As their power grew, the capital shifted multiple times, eventually crossing the Volta Gorge.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] In the south and west, the Fante people recount a migration from Bono-Tekyiman to the coast, where they encountered the Etsi.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Their founding is tied to Mankessim and the rock shrine Nananom Pow, linked to the legendary ancestral trio Obrumankoma, Odapagyan, and Oson.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Aowin (also known as Agni) claim an early presence in the western forests.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Their kingdom dominated regional trade and provided refuge to displaced groups before its decline during wars with Denkyira and Asante.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Sefwi people trace their origins to the Bono and Adansi areas but describe distinct migrations into the western forests in response to 17th–18th century warfare.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Nzima trace their origins to the formation of the Nzima Kingdom, created by three brothers, Annor Blay Ackah, Bua Kanyili, and Ahmiree II, who united the existing states of Jomoro, Abripiquem, and Ankobra through wealth gained from European trade.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Known in European records as Apolonia, this new polity dominated the south-western coast of the Gold Coast throughout the eighteenth century.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Further west, the Baoulé people of Côte d'Ivoire trace their ancestry to Akan groups who migrated westward from the Gold Coast in two waves during the early eighteenth century.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The first, known as the Alanguié Baoulé, moved from Denkyira after its defeat by the Asante around 1701, while the second, the Assabou group, left Kumasi following a disputed succession after the death of Osei Tutu in 1717.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] E1b1a1-M2 is the predominant paternal haplogroup in West Africa (70-97%).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] According to Shriner and Rotimi, genetic analysis suggests that the sickle-cell mutation originated about 7,300 years ago during the Holocene Wet Phase.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Their study found evidence for a single origin of the mutation in Africa, possibly in the Sahara or in west-central Africa, before it later spread across different populations on the continent.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] During the Holocene the Sahara experienced major climatic changes.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Around 11,000 years ago, during the African Humid Period, lakes, rivers, and grasslands spread across areas that are now desert.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Archaeological evidence shows that human populations lived across the Sahara during this time.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Between about 6300 and 5200 years ago the climate became dry again, population levels declined, and many desert regions were abandoned.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The earliest cultural developments in the Akan forest zone are associated with the Kintampo Complex (c.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] 2000–500 BCE), which marked the transition from foraging to sedentary village life.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Archaeological evidence from central Ghana reveals that early communities practiced mixed farming, kept domestic animals, and produced decorated ceramics, polished stone tools, and terracotta figurines.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] By the 5th century CE, northern forest communities had developed long-term settlements supported by agriculture, trade, and iron production.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Oral traditions from the Bono recall emergence from sacred caves like Amowi and the founding of Bono Manso.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Research at sites such as Kranka Dada revealed continuous occupation and participation in wider regional trade.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] By the 14th century, the Bono region was linked to the Niger trade routes.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Excavations at Bonoso, the first settlement of the Wankyi Bono, uncovered iron-smelting furnaces, slag, copper ornaments, and pottery, with radiocarbon dates between 660 and 1068 CE.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Nyarko quarter of Begho, named after the ancestress Efua Nyarko, was a proto-urban settlement dated to 965–1125 CE.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The site contained iron tools, copper objects, ivory, and painted pottery comparable to 9th-century finds from New Buipe.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] In the southern forests, Asantemanso was continuously occupied from at least the 9th century CE, with traces of earlier habitation possibly dating as far back as 700 BCE.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] It is remembered in local traditions as the ancestral origin of the Oyoko and Aduana clans.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Bono Manso consolidated into a polity between the 11th and 13th centuries.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] At its height, Bono Manso was recognized as the seat of the "Dua-duakwa hene mu hene" (king of many kings).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] By the 13th century, Begho had grown into a major commercial town.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Archaeological research shows it was predominantly Brong in culture, with distinct quarters for Mande-speaking Muslim merchants and craft specialists, including brassworkers at Dwinfuor and iron smelters at Dapaa, in the northwest.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Spindle whorls, dye pits, terracotta weights, and glass beads were among many items were present in the site.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Its position allowed it to link forest and savanna products to centers such as Jenne, Kong, and Bobo-Dioulasso.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] In the 14th century, Begho had become a cosmopolitan hub with copper and brass workshops, dyewells, imported Chinese porcelain, and Islamic gold weights.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Estimates place its population between 7,000 and 10,000, and was one of the largest settlements in precolonial Ghana.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Gold formed the backbone of Bono's economy, fueling both internal authority and external commerce.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Connections with trans-Saharan caravans grew as Dyula merchants exchanged brassware, cowries, textiles, and horses for gold, kola, and ivory.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Bono Manso, Wankyi, and Begho were integrated into this network.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Akan goldfields, and its associated settlements, came to be recognized as one of the three gold-producing regions, alongside Bambuk and Bure.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Archaeological parallels from Wenchi indicate that some of its early settlements were contemporaneous with Begho and Bono Manso, possibly dating to the 14th century, suggesting a wider regional development of northern Akan culture.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Adanse state emerged in the forest zone and is remembered in Akan cosmogony as the place “where God began creation”.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Local traditions identify Adansemanso as its first capital.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] It was regarded as the first among five foundational Akan polities, along with Akyem Kingdoms, Kingdom of Assin, Kingdom of Denkyira, and Asante, which are collectively known as the *Akanman Piesie Anum*.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Major clans such as the Ekouna, Asona, Bretuo, Oyoko, Asakyiri, Asenie, and Agona trace their origins to towns within its territory.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] By the 13th century, Adanse was integrated into Trans-Saharan trade networks through Wangara intermediaries, exchanging gold for Saharan goods.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Gold was mined in areas such as Akrokerri and Dompoase under ritual supervision invoking the deity Bona.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Statecraft was tied to control over goldfields, tribute, and military organization, with towns like Edubiase and Bodwesanwo producing iron weapons.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] At its peak in the 13th–15th centuries, Adansemanso was one of the largest ancient towns in the central forest zone, containing domestic structures, iron-smelting debris, and brass gold weights.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] In the 15th century, elite families with origins in Adansemanso and Asantemanso became wealthy through long-distance trade and established a political system known as *abirempondom*.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] These *obirempon* ruled from dominant towns that exercised authority over surrounding towns of free and unfree subjects, creating new forms of jurisdiction, land clearance, and court culture.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] As centralized states like Bonoman and Adanse developed, groups of Akan-speaking peoples began dispersing southward into the forest and coastal belts of southern Ghana.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] This movement was driven by the search for fertile land, access to gold resources, and emerging political dynamics in the interior.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] A southward migration led to the formation of the Fante, whose oral traditions trace their origins to inland centers such as Bono-Takyiman and Adanse.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] After settling near Mankessim, the Fante established a settlement, and the Nananom Pow, a sacred grove.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Before Portuguese contact in 1471, Akan communities were established along the coast.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] These groups maintained cultural and political ties to the interior.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] As these migrations increased, new settlements were founded in the forest zone, giving rise to gold-producing states such as Wassa, Aowin (Anyi or Agni), and others.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] According to oral traditions, the Aowin state of the Aowin (Agni) people grew to become the dominant power in the southwestern forest, controlling gold sources and trade routes to Apollonia and Begho.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Their territory later became a refuge for groups displaced by wars and territorial conflicts.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] In the late 16th century, Portuguese explorers encountered Akan-speaking merchants controlling gold routes from the forest interior to the coast.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Duarte Pacheco Pereira (1505–1508) listed inland traders as the Haccanys, Boroes, Bremus, Cacres, Andese, and Souzos, who brought gold from distant lands to the coast.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Some of the names are now understood as early references to Akan groups in the Pra–Ofin–Birim basin.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Portuguese writings described them as *cavaleiros mercadores* (“merchant knights”).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] A 1629 Dutch map marked three inland zones as “Akani,” which produced the finest gold, referred to as “Akan sika.” Portuguese forts like São Jorge da Mina were built to secure this trade, but the Akan states controlled gold production and supply.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] By the early 16th century, the inland Akan polities were facing growing internal and external pressures.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Portuguese records from 1502 mention a war between the Akan and Atis (Etsii), and in 1548 they noted a “civil war among the Akans”.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The European demand for gold and the introduction of firearms intensified the rivalries.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Akan polities began buying muskets through coastal trade and enslaved captives.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] In the 17th century onward, the Dutch, British, Danes, and Brandenburgers, intensified their presence along the coast, competing for access to the inland Akan goldfields.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] In return, they supplied firearms, gunpowder, and textiles.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Muskets quickly became important to state-building, and armed expansionism grew central to political survival across the region.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Overtime states such as Akwamu, Denkyira, Akyem, and Assin grew as militarized powers.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] These polities began expanding territory, controlling trade routes, and asserting political control.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] European writings from this period began distinguishing Great Accany with Akyem in the east, and Little Accany with the Kingdom of Assin in the south of the goldfields.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] As warfare escalated and tribute networks collapsed, the cohesion of the Akan heartland fractured.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The late 17th century saw the rise of Denkyira and Akwamu as the most dominant states.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] As Akwamu rose as a major Akan power, it began expanding eastward under Ansa Sasraku and capturing Accra by 1681, turning it into a tributary while collecting rents from European forts.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Denkyira, built on gold wealth and military conquest, imposed harsh demands on its tributaries under Boaponsem and laterNtim Gyakari, provoking widespread unrest.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Its imperial control sparked the rise of Osei Tutu and the Asante Empire.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] In the late 17th century, Osei Tutu, who returned from exile at Akwamu with political experience.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] With Anokye, unified clans and created the Golden Stool, the symbol of Asante nationhood.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] In 1699, Asante challenged Denkyira, whose tributaries, joined the revolt.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Denkyira's firearm supply was cut off, and in 1701 it was defeated at the Battle of Feyiase.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Asante then centralized power and expanded rapidly.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] By 1709, it was a dominant force inland.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] As Asante power extended southwestward, it came into direct conflict with the Aowin (Agni) state, which had previously dominated the region between the Tano and Bia.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] In 1715, Asante forces under General Amankwatia, aided by their Wiawso allies. they launched a major campaign against Aowin.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] As Aowin declined, incoming migrants from Bono, Adanse, and Denkyira established three autonomous but related states: Sefwi Wiawso, Sefwi Bekwai, and Sefwi Anhwiaso, which absorbed cultural influences from neighboring Akan polities.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] In 1722–1723 internal succession disputes and the unpopular rule of Ameyaw Kwakye had already weakened Bono's authority, and Asante forces quickly overran the town, capturing its rulers and artisans, and relocating regalia and treasury assets to Kumase.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Many Bono fled to Techiman, while others migrated westward regrouping in nearby locations like Gyaman, Abease, and the Banda area.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Wars during this period caused the Baoulé and other splinter groups seeking refuge from Asante expansion.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Many people across the Americas trace their ancestry to Akan-speaking populations due to the trans-Atlantic slave trade.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Between the 17th and 19th centuries, a significant proportion of enslaved Africans shipped from the Gold Coast, estimated at 10% of all embarkations from West Africa were of Akan origin.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Internal conflicts among the Akan states during the 17th to 18th centuries, led to the capture and selling of war captives.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Akan captives, labeled as “Coromantee” in British colonies, gained a reputation for resistance and military discipline.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Many were former soldiers from warring states like Fante, Akwamu or Ashanti, and their skills were transferred to plantation and maroon communities.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] They played central roles in uprisings across the Americas, including the 1733 Akwamu-led revolt on St.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] John, the 1760 Tacky's Rebellion in Jamaica, and the 1763 Berbice uprising in Guyana led by Coffy, a Coromantee war captain.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Some Coromantee, such as Chief Takyi in Jamaica, were former warlords turned rebels who attempted to recreate Akan-style governance during these revolts.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] In several colonies, colonial authorities even feared large concentrations of Coromantee slaves, associating them with rebellion and political organization.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Asante Empire emerged as the dominant military and commercial power in the forest zone by the early 18th century.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] It controlled trade routes extending from the savanna hinterlands in the north to the Atlantic coast, extracting tribute and asserting influence over formerly independent states.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Asante's control over goldfields and strategic corridors put it in direct competition with coastal states like the Fante Confederacy.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] In response to rising Asante power and European trade pressures, the Fante reorganized in the mid-18th century into a defensive coalition of city-states led from Mankessim.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Fante developed a distinct political identity influenced by diplomacy with European powers and rivalry with Asante.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Fante Confederacy had become a key player along the coast, defending its territory through alliances with the British and resisting inland incursions.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] After clashes between the Asante and the British occurred, treaties by Thomas Bowdich (1817) and William Dupuis (1820) failed to end long-term hostilities.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Anglo-Ashanti wars erupted in cycles, with the 1824 battle at Nsamankow, the 1826 defeat at Katamanso, and the 1874 British invasion of Kumasi, which led to the looting of the palace and destruction of regalia.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Asante remained autonomous until 1900, when a final confrontation over British demands for the Golden Stool triggered the War of the Golden Stool.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Led by Yaa Asantewaa, Queen Mother of Ejisu, Asante resistance culminated in the siege of Kumasi, the exile of Asantehene Prempeh I, and Asante's formal incorporation into the British colony by 1901.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Meanwhile, Gyaman engaged with French expansion in the western Sudan.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] In 1888, the Gyamanhene signed a protection treaty with France to resist Asante and British encroachment.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] France failed to assert control, and in 1895, Samori Touré launched a campaign that destabilized the region.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] After the French expelled Samori in 1897, Gyaman was partitioned: the western zone, including Bonduku, was annexed into French West Africa, while the eastern section, centered on Sampa, became part of the British Protectorate.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] On the coast, states such as the Fante Confederacy and others were gradually brought under indirect British rule through treaties.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] By the early 20th century, nearly all Akan territories had been absorbed into the colonial territories of the British Gold Coast and the French Colonial Empire.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] In central Côte d'Ivoire, the Baoulé also resisted colonial occupation.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] In 1906, Governor Gabriel Angoulvant launched a military campaign to forcibly subdue Baoulé chiefdoms, marking one of the last major uprisings against French rule in the region.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] On 6th March 1957, under the leadership of Kwame Nkrumah and the Convention People's Party, the Gold Coast became the first sub-Saharan African colony to achieve independence from European colonial rule.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The new nation was renamed Ghana, symbolically connecting modern statehood to the region's historic legacy of powerful African empires.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The territory united the Gold Coast colony with British Togoland, as well as the Northern and Upper regions.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Across the border, neighboring Ivory Coast gained independence from France in 1960 under the leadership of Félix Houphouët-Boigny, a prominent Baoulé figure who had served as a French parliamentarian.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] As president, Houphouët-Boigny oversaw the establishment of a centralized state that integrated traditional Akan political culture with republican governance.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Like Ghana, Ivory Coast is home to a significant Akan population with 40% of the national total.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] In 1969, the Sanwi kingdom of Krinjabo, famously attempted to secede from Ivory Coast and restore monarchical rule.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Akans consider themselves one nation.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Akan means first, foremost, indicating the enlightened and civilized.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] While traditionally matrilineal, they are also united philosophically through 12 patrilineal spirit groups called the Ntoro*.* Within the Akan nation are branches based on many dialects, widest and possibly the oldest one being used is Twi as well as Fante.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Each branch subsequently holds a collection of states and stemming from city-states.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The state or **Ɔman** are typically ruled by several kings known as **Amanhene** (*Ɔmanhene*, singular) or **Ahemfo** (*Ɔhene*, singular).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The state is the basic unit of Akan polity.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Several states and city-states can band together to form a confederacy or an empire regardless of clan or abusua they belong to, while those outsides of the Akan people or the abusua were usually conquered or annexed via war or mutual agreement.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] For example, the Guan state of Larteh and the Akyem state of Akropong joined to form the Akwapim Kingdom to avoid the Akwamu, who the Guan deemed as oppressive.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Under the State there are Divisions and under these Divisions are towns and villages.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Akan kings are ranked according to their jurisdiction.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The head of an inter-clan Confederacy is usually considered a King, as in the Kings of Ashanti, Fante, Akyem and the Akwapim.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Under these are the heads of the constituent states who equates an Emperor that only heads an Empire (e.g., Asante Empire and the Denkyira).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] In Asante's case, as an Empire, the Asantehene reigned over the non-Oyoko clan city-states and ruled over the kings of those states as an Imperial head or Emperor (a hardly used but an equivalent term for Emperor or *the king of kings*).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Next there are divisional Chiefs, they are primarily arranged according to the five divisions of an Akan army.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Fante army or Asafo formation resembles a cross or an airplane.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Fante battle formations eventually had some European influences and many Asafo Frankaa (battle flags) incorporated the British Union Jack after 1844 when they allied with them.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The battle formation has the Frontline, the West Flank, an East Flank, the main body and the Vanguard.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] There are, therefore, five divisional chiefs in each Paramountcy.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] These are followed in rank by the Kings of the city and then the Kings of the town and then king of the suburbs.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Akan peoples mostly have seven Abusua (Matrilineal clans/tribes) in each state.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] They do not have the same names in each state but each has an equivalent clan (e.g. in Fante areas along the coast, the Asante clan of Oyoko is referred to as Dehyena or Yokofo).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The clans are assigned States which they rule by their status as founders of that jurisdiction.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Ashanti Kingdom is ruled by the Oyoko Clan.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] However, the Bretuo or Twidanfo (in Fante), as well as other clans, rule States, Divisions, Towns, and Villages within the Kingdom.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Fante-speaking peoples usually have the Asona Clan ruling most of their States (like Mankessim).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Certain sub-clans or lineages have exclusive rights to some stools within Akanland such as the lineage of Afia Kobi in the Oyoko Clan who alone sits on the Golden Stool of Asante.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Akans are traditionally a Matrilineal people of the African continent.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Matrilineal inheritance makes it easier to trace the line of succession.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Within each lineage or House are the branches.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The chief of a family is called an *Abusuapanyin* (or family-elder).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Ranking above a family chief (a family's Abusuapanyin) is the clan's chief (or clan's Abusuapanyin).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] These branches are called Jaase/Gyaase or Kitchens.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Each Kitchen takes its turn to present a candidate for the stool to the kingmakers of the lineage.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Once accepted their candidate rules till death.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] This means until all the Jaase have presented their candidates they have to wait their turn.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Akan Kings of whatever rank have other nobleman who serve them as sub-chiefs.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] These sub-chiefs do not have hereditary titles and therefore do not have black stools.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Besides, each King has a female co-ruler known as the Queen-mother.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] They present the candidate for consideration as King.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] An assistant king does not have a Queen-mother as his title is not hereditary.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] A Prince or Daakyehen (Fante, literally *Future-king*) is any of the members of the lineage eligible to sit on a stool.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] However, not all royals are Princes as some may be ineligible.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] A prince is not necessarily the son of a King but rather the former King's nephew on the mother's side.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] As such, royals strive to achieve the position of a prince in their families or for their children.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] All Akan clans are considered royal in the context of their matrilineal society.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Each clan, known as *abusua*, plays a significant role in inheritance, succession, and the selection of chiefs.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The eight main Akan clans—Oyoko, Bretuo, Agona, Asona, Asenie, Aduana, Ekuona, and Asakyiri—are integral to the governance of their respective communities.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Members of these clans are viewed as royals, as chiefs are traditionally chosen from them, reinforcing their royal status within Akan culture.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] A sub-chief does not, however, need to be a nobleman.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] He only has to be suitable for the position he is to occupy.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Some sub-chieftaincy positions can be abolished at will.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] They include the heads of the ruling house or Mankrado, the Linquist, the Chief Kingmaker or Jaasehen/Gyaasehen, the Supi (Fante) or General of the Army, the Captains of the Army or Asafohen (Fante) among others.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The way Akans ruled their nation fascinated the tribes and peoples of other West African nations and as the Akans conquered or formed alliances with these nations, parts of it were transmitted to them.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The British particularly felt the Akan system was highly efficient and tried to establish it throughout their dominions in West Africa using the Indirect Rule System.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Ewes and the Ga-Adangmes with their close affinity to the Akans have modified certain aspects of it to fit their societies.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] In Ghana and other modern states where the Akan people are located, the Kings, Assistant Kings, Princes, and Noblemen of the Akans serve mostly a symbolic role.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Modern politics has side-lined them in national politics although it is common to find that an elected or appointed official to be of Akan royalty.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] And, especially in the villages and poor areas, traditional Kings are still very important for organizing development, social services and keeping the peace.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Some Kings have decided to push ahead with the leadership of their Kingdoms and States in a non-political fashion.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Asantehen and okyehen have emphasized Education and Environmental Sustainability respectively.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Others push the national government and its agents to fulfill promises to their people.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Several Akan Kings sit at the various levels of the National House of "Chiefs".
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Each Paramountcy has a Traditional Council, then there is the Regional House of "Chiefs" and lastly the National House of "Chiefs".
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Akan Kings who once warred with each other and Kings of other nations within Ghana now sit with them to build peace and advocate development for their nations.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The identity of an Akan nation or meta-ethnicity is expressed by the term *Akanman*.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Akan word *ɔman* (*plural Aman*) which forms the second element in this expression has a meaning much of "community, town, nation, state".
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] *(A)man* has been translated as "Akanland".
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Akan refers to the language of the Akan ethnolinguistic group and the Akan language which was and is the most widely spoken and used indigenous language in the Akan peoples in Ghana.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Each ethnic group having its own dialect Akan is officially recognized for literacy in the Akan-majority regions, at the primary and elementary educational stage (Primary 1–3) K–12 (education) level, and studied at university as a bachelor's degree or master's degree program.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Akan language is spoken as the predominant language in the Western, Central, Ashanti, Eastern, Brong Ahafo regions of the akan clan.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] With the present state of technology, one can listen to live radio broadcasts in Akan from numerous radio stations and receive mass media and public broadcasts in Akan from numerous multimedia and media broadcasting.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Akan is studied in major universities in North America and the United States, including Ohio University, Ohio State University, University of Wisconsin–Madison, Harvard University, Boston University, Indiana University, University of Michigan, and the University of Florida.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Akan language has been a regular language of study in the annual Summer Cooperative African Languages Institute (SCALI) program and the Akan language is regulated and administered by the Akan Orthography Committee (AOC).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Some of Akan's language characteristic features include tone, vowel harmony, and nasalization.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Akan culture is one of the traditional matrilineal cultures of Africa.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Akan art is wide-ranging and renowned, especially for the tradition of crafting bronze gold weights, using the lost-wax casting method.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The Akan culture reached South America, the Caribbean, and North America.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Some of their most important mythological stories are called *anansesem*, literally meaning "the spider story", but in a figurative sense also meaning "traveler's tales".
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] These "spider stories" are sometimes also referred to as *nyankomsem*: "words of a sky god".
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The stories generally, but not always, revolve around Kwaku Ananse, a trickster spirit, often depicted as a spider, human, or a combination thereof.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Many but not all of the Akan still practice their traditional matrilineal customs, living in their traditional extended family households.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The traditional Akan economic and political organization is based on matrilineal *lineages*, which are the basis of inheritance and succession.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] A *lineage* is defined as all those related by matrilineal descent from a particular ancestress.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Several lineages are grouped into a political unit headed by a council of elders, each of whom is the elected head of a lineage – which itself may include multiple extended-family households.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Public offices are, thus, vested in the lineage, as are land tenure and other lineage property.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] In other words, lineage property is inherited only by matrilineal kin.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Each lineage controls the lineage land farmed by its members, functions together in the veneration of its ancestors, supervises marriages of its members, and settles internal disputes among its members.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The political units above are likewise grouped (into traditionally seven) but as of today, eight larger groups called *abusua*: Aduana, Agona, Asakyiri, Asenie, Asona, Bretuo, Ekuona, and Oyoko.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The members of each such *abusua* are united by their belief that they are all descended from the same ancient ancestress – so marriage between members of the same group (or *abusua*) is forbidden, a taboo on marriage.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] One inherits or is a lifelong member of, the lineage, the political unit and the *abusua* of one's mother, regardless of one's gender or marriage.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Members and their spouses thus belong to different *abusuas*, with mother and children living and working in one household, and their husband/father living and working in a different household.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] According to one source of information about the Akan, "A man is strongly related to his mother's brother (wɔfa) but only weakly related to his father's brother.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] This is perhaps viewed in the context of a polygamous society in which the mother/child bond is likely to be much stronger than the father/child bond.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] As a result, in inheritance, a man's nephew (his sister's son) (wɔfase) will have priority over his own son.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Finally, "it is when all possible male heirs have been exhausted that the females" may inherit.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Certain other aspects of the Akan culture are determined patrilineally rather than matrilineally.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] There are ancestrally 12 patrilineal *Ntoro* (spirit) groups, and everyone belongs to his or her father's *Ntoro* group, but not to his family lineage and *abusua*.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Each *Ntoro* group has its own surnames, taboos, ritual purifications, and forms of etiquette.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] A person thus inherits one's *Ntoro* from one's father but does not belong to his family.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] A recent (2001) book provides an update on the Akan, stating that some families are changing from the above *abusua* structure to the nuclear family.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] Housing, childcare, education, daily work, and elder care, etc. are then handled by that individual family, rather than by the *abusua* or clan, especially in the city.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-ethnic-group] The above taboo on marriage within one's *abusua* is sometimes ignored, but "clan membership" is still important, with many people still living in the *abusua* framework presented above.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Three dialects of Twi-Fante were developed as literary standards with distinct orthographies: Asante Twi, Akuapem Twi, and Fante.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Despite being mutually intelligible, they were inaccessible in written form to speakers of the other standards until the Akan Orthography Committee (AOC)'s development of a common Twi-Fante orthography in 1978, based mainly on Akuapem dialect.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] As the first Akan variety to be used for Bible translation, Akuapem Twi had become the prestige dialect.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] With the Atlantic slave trade, Akan languages, principally Twi/Fante, were introduced to the Caribbean and South America, notably in Suriname and Jamaica, where they heavily influenced the language of the Ndyuka and the Jamaican Maroons, also known as the Coromantee.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] The cultures of the descendants of escaped slaves in the interior of Suriname and the Maroons in Jamaica still retain Akan influences, including the Akan naming practice of naming children after the day of the week on which they are born, e.g.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Akwasi/Kwasi for a boy or Akosua for a girl born on a Sunday, etc.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] In Jamaica and Suriname, the *Ananse* spider stories are still well-known.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Originally, the language was known by local names rather than a single unifying term.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Inland Akan groups referred to it as 'Twi' (/tʃwiː, twiː, tʃiː/; Akan: [tɕᶣi]), while coastal Akan groups referred to it as 'Fante'.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] After independence, the national language commission adopted 'Akan', a name that had been used for all the languages spoken by the Akan people, which includes the Bia languages in addition to Twi-Fante, as a unitary name for Twi-Fante specifically.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] The broader scope was renamed Central Tano to avoid ambiguity.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] However, many sources still refer to all the languages spoken by the Akan people as 'Akan'.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] The largest Akan migration was to Ghana in successive waves between the 11th and 18th centuries.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Smaller numbers migrated to the eastern part of Côte d'Ivoire and parts of Togo.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Within Ghana, the Akan expanded from the north to occupy the southern forest and coastal areas during the 13th century.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] The Akans have a strong oral history tradition of their past and are also known in for symbolic artifacts of wood, metal and terracotta.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Their cultural ideas are expressed in stories and proverbs as well as in designs such as symbols used in carvings and on clothes.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] The rich Akan culture and history in Ghana are areas of research for many disciplines, such as folklore, literary studies, linguistics, anthropology, and history.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Twi-Fante is a dialect continuum that is closely related to the Bia languages and the other Akan languages that are spoken by the Akan people.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Brong and Wasa have limited mutual intelligibility with each other, and so are separate languages by that standard.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Neighboring Brong and Asante are mutually intelligible, though geographically more distant Brong and Fante are less so.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] The Twi-Fante dialects contain extensive palatalization, vowel harmony, and tone terracing.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Before front vowels, all Asante consonants are palatalized (or labio-palatalized), and the stops are to some extent affricated.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] The allophones of /n/ are quite complex.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] In the table below, palatalized allophones which involve more than minor phonetic palatalization are specified, in the context of the vowel /i/.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] These sounds do occur before other vowels, such as /a/, though in most cases not commonly.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] In Asante, /ɡu/ followed by a vowel is pronounced /ɡʷ/, but in Akuapem it remains /ɡu/.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] A word final /k/ can be heard as a glottal stop [ʔ].
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] There is also a nasalization of /h/ and of /j w/ as [h̃] and [j̃ w̃], when occurring before nasal vowels.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] The transcriptions in the tables below are in the order /phonemic/, [phonetic].
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Note that orthographic ⟨dw⟩ is ambiguous; in textbooks, ⟨dw⟩ = /ɡ/ may be distinguished from /dw/ with a diacritic: *d̩w*.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Likewise, velar ⟨nw⟩ (ŋw) may be transcribed *n̩w*.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] All fourteen were distinguished in the Gold Coast alphabet of the colonial era.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] A tongue-root distinction in orthographic *a* is only found in some subdialects of Fante, but not in the literary form; in Asante and Akuapem there are harmonic allophones of /a/, but neither is ATR.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] The two vowels written *e* (/e/ and /i̙/) and *o* (/o/ and /u̙/) are often not distinguished in pronunciation.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Twi-Fante vowels engage in a form of vowel harmony with the root of the tongue.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] After the +RTR non-high vowels /e̙ a̙ o̙/, −RTR mid vowels /e o/ become +RTR high vowels /i̙ u̙/.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] This is not reflected in the orthography, for both sets of vowels are spelled ⟨e o⟩, and in many dialects this rule does not apply, for these vowels have merged.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Initial syllable may only be *high* or *low*.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] The phonetic pitch of the three tones depends on their environment, often being lowered after other tones, producing a steady decline known as tone terracing.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] /H/ tones have the same pitch as a preceding /H/ or /M/ tone within the same tonic phrase, whereas /M/ tones have a lower pitch.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] That is, the sequences /HH/ and /MH/ have a level pitch, whereas the sequences /HM/ and /MM/ have a falling pitch. /H/ is lowered (downstepped) after a /L/.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] /L/ is the default tone, which emerges in situations such as reduplicated prefixes.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] It is always at bottom of the speaker's pitch range, except in the sequence /HLH/, in which case it is raised in pitch but the final /H/ is still lowered.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Thus /HMH/ and /HLH/ are pronounced with distinct but very similar pitches.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] After the first "prominent" syllable of a clause, usually the first high tone, there is a downstep.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Twi-Fante historically employed a noun class system similar to that of Bantu languages.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Although this system is now largely defunct, remnants of it persist in modern Twi-Fante plural formation, particularly through prefixes and suffixes.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] The current pluralisation system blends fossilised class prefixes with newer morphological strategies, especially for human nouns.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Notably, human nouns have preserved more elements of the old system than non-human nouns and can employ multiple plural-marking strategies simultaneously.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Modern Twi-Fante employs several strategies for plural formation, representing a transition from its historical purely prefixal system to a mixed system using both prefixes and suffixes.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] These strategies vary based on semantic categories, with human nouns showing particularly complex patterns.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Many Twi-Fante nouns form their plurals through the addition or replacement of nasal prefixes (*m-*, *n-*), reflecting remnants of the old noun class system.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] In this process, the original class prefix (typically *a-*) is replaced by a homorganic nasal prefix that assimilates to the initial consonant of the root word.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] For example, initial *ab-* becomes *mm-* and *ad-* becomes *nn-* in plural forms.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] A relatively newer morphological development involves using plural suffixes, primarily for human and agentive nouns.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] This development is particularly significant as it shows how Twi-Fante is evolving from its historical prefix-based system.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Human nouns demonstrate the most complex plural marking, often combining both old prefixal and new suffixal strategies — a pattern that highlights their special status in the language's grammatical system.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] This suffix is used primarily for kinship and social role terms.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] This suffix is used with profession- or agent-based nouns.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] In some cases, both a prefix and a suffix are used for pluralisation, especially with human nouns (e.g., *onua* → *enuanom*).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] This double marking represents a unique development in the Twi-Fante plural system, where human nouns have not only preserved elements of the old class system but have also incorporated new morphological strategies, resulting in a more complex marking pattern than non-human nouns.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Certain Twi-Fante nouns remain unchanged in the plural, representing another way the historical noun class system has been simplified.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] While human nouns have developed complex plural marking strategies, these invariant nouns — including mass nouns and inherently plural items — have moved in the opposite direction by eliminating plural marking entirely.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Twi-Fante originally featured a more extensive system of noun classes marked by singular/plural prefixes.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Over time, this class system has undergone morphological decay.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Modern Twi-Fante lacks productive class agreement between nouns and adjectives or verbs, and many prefixes have become fossilised elements perceived as part of the noun stem.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] The letters C, J, Q, V, X and Z are also used, but only in loanwords.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] The Akan languages have a rich literature in proverbs, folktales, and traditional drama, as well as a new literature in dramas, short stories, and novels.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] This literature began to be documented in written form in the late 1800s.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Later, Joseph Hanson Kwabena Nketia collected a number of proverbs and folktales, including *Funeral Dirges of the Akan People* (1969), *Folk Songs of Ghana* (1963), and *Akan Poetry* (1958).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Some of the important authors in the language are A.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] The Bureau of Ghana Languages has been unable to continue printing novels in the language, and the following are out of print: *Obreguo, Okrabiri, Afrakoma, Obeede, Fia Tsatsala,*and *Ku Di Fo Nanawu*.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] In 1978 the AOC established a unified "Akan" orthography for Twi-Fante, which is used as the medium of instruction in primary school.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Literacy in Twi-Fante is counted toward general literacy, from at least the lower primary level (primary 1–3).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Twi-Fante is studied at several major universities in the United States, including Ohio University, Ohio State University, University of Wisconsin-Madison, Harvard University, Boston University, Indiana University, University of Michigan, and The University of Florida.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Twi-Fante has been a regular African language of study in the annual Summer Cooperative African Languages Institute (SCALI) program.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] The Twi-Fante language is studied in these universities as a bachelor or masters program.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] The Akan people use a common naming system of giving the first name to a child, based on the day of the week that the child was born.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/akan-language] Most of the nations in Ghana have a similar custom, which extends to neighboring countries.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] American Sign Language (ASL) has grammar just like any other sign language or spoken language.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The study of ASL structure dates back to William Stokoe, Dorothy Casterline, and Carl Croneberg in the 1960s.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Since then, linguists have been describing patterns in ASL responsible for creating meaning at all kinds of levels, from the word, to phrases and sentences and beyond.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Not all of these linguists ascribe to the same theoretical framework, using various theories, models, and analyses.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some analyze the language from a generative linguistics perspective, while others from a cognitive linguistics perspective.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL morphology, publications have historically categorized morphological processes under two umbrellas: derivational morphology and inflectional morphology.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Derivational morphology is the process by which new units can be created in a language, and like any other language, this process has been observed in a variety of forms in ASL.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] One form of derivational morphology occurs when a change in movement changes the sign's meaning – often between a noun and a verb.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This may be done either by reduplicating the movement of the verb if the verb has a single movement, or by restraining (making smaller and faster) the movement of the verb if it already has repeated movement.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the noun CHAIR is derived from the verb SIT through reduplication.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Another way of deriving new words in ASL is via the process of compounding, which often differ in meaning from their constituent signs.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the signs FACE and STRONG compound to create a new sign FACE^STRONG, meaning 'to resemble'.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some linguists have analyzed various compounds as a type of suffixation.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Agent nouns may be derived from verbs by adding the sign, or suffix, AGENT and deleting the final hold of the verb, e.g.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Superlatives have also been analyzed as created by a formed by suffixation, e.g.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, Ted Supalla's work on ASL verbs of motion analyzed these signs as consisting of many different affixes, articulated simultaneously according to complex grammatical constraints.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This differs from the concatenative morphology of many spoken languages, which except for suprasegmental features, such as tone, are tightly constrained by the sequential nature of voice sounds.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Numeral incorporation is another derivational morphological process that has been studied in ASL.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Certain types of signs, for example, those relating to time and age, may incorporate numbers by assimilating their handshape.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the word for 'week' has handshape /B/ with the weak hand and /1/ with the active hand; the active hand's handshape may be changed to the handshape of any number up to 9 to indicate that many weeks.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some linguists have analyzed this phenomenon as a type of affixation.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Signs of age, for example, will begin with a touch at the chin.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They argue that this touch functions as a prefix which completely assimilates with the handshape of the corresponding age number.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For instance, the word for 'nine' is signed with an /F/ handshape produced ipsilaterally in front of the signer's shoulder.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The chin-touch in 'nine years old' can be analyzed as an affix, which is then produced with this same /F/ handshape.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For 'three years old', however, the prefix is made with a 3 handshape.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Inflectional morphology adds units of language to other words.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, this would be changing 'watch' to 'watches' or 'watching.' In ASL, the sign may remain unchanged as WATCH, or the meaning may change based on non-manual markers (NMM).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL morphology demonstrates reduplication and indexicality as well.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are about 20 non-manual modifiers in ASL, which are either adjectival or adverbial.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Rather than relying on sequential affixes, ASL makes heavy use of simultaneous modification of signs.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] One example of this is found in the aspectual system (see below); another is *numeral incorporation:* There are several families of two-handed signs which require one of the hands to take the handshape of a numeral.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, drawing the dominant hand lengthwise across the palm and fingers of a flat B hand indicates a number of weeks; the dominant hand takes the form of a numeral from one to nine to specify how many weeks.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are analogous signs for 'weeks ago' and 'weeks from now', etc., though in practice several of these signs are only found with the lower numerals.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL also has a system of classifiers which may be incorporated into signs.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These classifiers are moved through sign space to iconically represent the actions of their referents.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, an ILY hand may 'lift off' or 'land on' a horizontal B hand to sign an aircraft taking off or landing; a 3 hand may be brought down on a B hand to sign parking a car; and a G hand may be brought toward a V hand to represent one person approaching two.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The frequency of classifier use depends greatly on genre, occurring at a rate of 17.7% in narratives but only 1.1% in casual speech and 0.9% in formal speech.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Frames are a morphological device that may be unique to sign languages (Liddell 2004).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They are incomplete sets of the features which make up signs, and they combine with existing signs, absorbing features from them to form a derived sign.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It is the frame which specifies the number and nature of segments in the resulting sign, while the basic signs it combines with lose all but one or two of their original features.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] One, the WEEKLY frame, consists of a simple downward movement.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It combines with the signs for the days of the week, which then lose their inherent movement.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, 'Monday' consists of an M/O hand made with a circling movement.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] 'MondayWEEKLY' (that is, 'on Mondays') is therefore signed as an M/O hand that drops downward, but without the circling movement.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] A similar ALL DAY frame (a sideward pan) combines with times of the day, such as 'morning' and 'afternoon', which likewise keep their handshape and location but lose their original movement.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Numeral incorporation (see above) also uses frames.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, in ASL frames are most productively utilized for verbal aspect.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] While there is no grammatical tense in ASL, there are numerous verbal aspects.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These are produced by modulating the verb: through reduplication, by placing the verb in an aspectual frame (see above), or with a combination of these means.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] An example of an aspectual frame is the *unrealized inceptive* aspect ('just about to X'), illustrated here with the verb 'to tell'.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] 'To tell' is an indexical (directional) verb, where the index finger (a G hand) begins with a touch to the chin and then moves outward to point out the recipient of the telling.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The handshape throughout the sign is whichever is required by the final hold, in this case a G hand.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The variety of aspects in ASL can be illustrated by the verb 'to be sick', which involves the middle finger of the Y/8 hand touching the forehead, and which can be modified by a large number of frames.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Several of these involve reduplication, which may but need not be analyzed as part of the frame.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These modulations readily combine with each other to create yet finer distinctions.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Not all verbs take all aspects, and the forms they do take will not necessarily be completely analogous to the verb illustrated here.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Conversely, not all aspects are possible with this one verb.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Aspect is unusual in ASL in that transitive verbs derived for aspect lose their transitivity.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Reduplication is also used for expressing verbal number.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Verbal number indicates that the action of the verb is repeated; in the case of ASL it is apparently limited to transitive verbs, where the motion of the verb is either extended or repeated to cover multiple object or recipient loci.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] (Simple plurality of action can also be conveyed with reduplication, but without indexing any object loci; in fact, such aspectual forms do not allow objects, as noted above.) There are specific dual forms (and for some signers trial forms), as well as plurals.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the singular verb uses reduplication, that is lost in the dual and plural forms.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are three types of personal name signs in ASL: fingerspelled, arbitrary, and descriptive.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Fingerspelled names are simply spelled out letter-by-letter.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Arbitrary name signs only refer to a person's name, while descriptive name signs refer to a person's personality or physical characteristics.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Once given, names are for life, apart from changing from one of the latter types to an arbitrary sign in childhood.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Name signs are usually assigned by another member of the Deaf community, and signal inclusion in that community.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Name signs are not used to address people, as names are in English, but are used only for third-person reference, and usually only when the person is absent.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The majority of people, probably well in excess of 90%, have arbitrary name signs.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These are initialized signs: The handshape is the initial of one of the English names of the person, usually the first.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The sign may occur in neutral space, with a tremble; with a double-tap (as a noun) at one of a limited number of specific locations, such as the side of the chin, the temple, or the elbow; or moving across a location or between two locations, with a single tap at each.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Single-location signs are simpler in connotation, like English "Vee"; double-location signs are fancier, like English "Veronica".
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Sam Supalla (1992) collected 525 simple arbitrary name signs like these.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are two constraints on arbitrary signs.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] That is, it should not duplicate an existing ASL word.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Second, there should not be more than one person with the name sign in the local community.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If a person moves to a new community where someone already has their name sign, then the newcomer is obligated to modify theirs.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is usually accomplished by compounding the handshape, so that the first tap of the sign takes the initial of the person's first English name, and the second tap takes the initial of their last name.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are potentially thousands of such compound-initial signs.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Descriptive name signs are not initialized, but rather use non-core ASL signs.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They tend to be assigned and used by children, rather like "Blinky" in English.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Parents do not give such names to their children, but most Deaf people do not have deaf parents and are assigned their name sign by classmates in their first school for the deaf.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] At most 10% of Deaf people retain such name signs into adulthood..
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Arbitrary name signs became established very early in the history of ASL.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Descriptive name signs refer to a person's appearance or personality.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The two systems, arbitrary and descriptive, are sometimes combined, usually for humorous purposes.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Hearing people learning ASL are also often assigned combined name signs.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is not traditional for Deaf people.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Sometimes people with very short English names, such as "Ann" or "Lee", or ones that flow easily, such as "Larry", may never acquire a name sign, but may instead be referred to with finger-spelling.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-Manual Markers (NMM), or Non-Manual Signals (NMS) are communication methods not found in the hands.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They typically consist of facial expressions and body language.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] NMMs can change the grammar of a sentence.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Not every sign uses non-manual markers, but for many others, these markers determine what sign is being produced.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some examples of non-manual markers would be the shifting of shoulders, the lowering or raising of eyebrows, a head nod or shake, scrunching of the nose, pursing of the lips, or an open mouth.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] NMMs are important for indicating if a question is being asked.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For *WH-* questions, the eyebrows are lowered, and for *YES/NO* questions, the eyebrows are raised.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It is hard to indicate if a question is being asked otherwise without facial indicators.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Another example would be between *I UNDERSTAND* and *I DON'T UNDERSTAND*.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The sign for this is the same; the hand is held up near the forehead with the palm facing the self.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the person is nodding and has their eyebrows raised, it means *I UNDERSTAND*.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If they are shaking their head with eyebrows lowered, it means *I DON'T UNDERSTAND*.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Understanding ASL grammar requires understanding the difference between a signer's dominant and non-dominant hand.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If a person is right-handed, then their right hand is their dominant hand, and their left hand is their non-dominant hand.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Almost all signs are completed with the more active, dominant hand, while the non-dominant hand serves as a base.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For signs requiring two hands, the dominant hand performs more of the active component.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL is a subject–verb–object (SVO) language.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, OSV is also an accepted sentence form.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The default SVO word order is sometimes altered by processes including topicalization and null elements.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is marked either with non-manual signals like eyebrow or body position, or with prosodic marking such as pausing.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These non-manual grammatical markings (such as eyebrow movement or head-shaking) may optionally spread over the c-command domain of the node which it is attached to.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, ASL is a pro-drop language, and when the manual sign that a non-manual grammatical marking is attached to is omitted, the non-manual marking obligatorily spreads over the c-command domain.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The full sentence structure in ASL is [topic] [subject] verb [object] [subject–pronoun–tag].
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topics and *tags* are both indicated with non-manual features, and both give a great deal of flexibility to ASL word order.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Within a noun phrase, the word order is noun–number and noun–adjective.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL does not have a copula (linking 'to be' verb).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In addition to its basic topic–comment structure, ASL typically places an adjective after a noun, though it may occur before the noun for stylistic purposes.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Numerals also occur after the noun, a very rare pattern among oral languages.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Adverbs, however, occur before the verbs.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Most of the time adverbs are simply the same sign as an adjective, distinguished by the context of the sentence.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] When the scope of the adverb is the entire clause, as in the case of time, it comes before the topic.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL makes heavy use of time-sequenced ordering, meaning that events are signed in the order in which they occur.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, for *I was late to class last night because my boss handed me a huge stack of work after lunch yesterday,* one would sign 'YESTERDAY LUNCH FINISH, BOSS GIVE-me WORK BIG-STACK, NIGHT CLASS LATE-me'.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In stories, however, ordering is malleable, since one can choose to sequence the events either in the order in which they occurred or in the order in which one found out about them.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It has been claimed that tense in ASL is marked adverbially, and that ASL lacks a separate category of tense markers.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] (1992, 1995) argue that "Tense" (T) is indeed a distinct category of syntactic head, and that the T node can be occupied either by a modal (e.g.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Aspect may be marked either by verbal inflection or by separate lexical items.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] As noted above, in ASL aspectually marked verbs cannot take objects.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] To deal with this, the object must be known from context so that it does not need to be further specified.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It may be used as the topic of the utterance at hand.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Of these two strategies, the first is the more common.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] A topic sets off background information that will be discussed in the following main clause.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topicalization is used productively in ASL and often results in surface forms that do not follow the basic SVO word order.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In order to non-manually mark topics, the eyebrows are raised and the head is tilted back during the production of a topic.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The head is often lowered toward the end of the sign, and sometimes the sign is followed rapidly nodding the head.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Another way topics may be signed is by shifting the body.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The signer may use the space on one side of his/her body to sign the topic, and then shifts to the other side for the rest of the sentence.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL utterances do not require topics, but their use is extremely common.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They are used for purposes of information flow, to set up referent loci (see above), and to supply objects for verbs which are grammatically prevented from taking objects themselves (see below).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, people tend to want to set up the object of their concern first and then discuss what happened to it.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are three types of non-manual topic markers, all of which involve raised eyebrows.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The three types of non-manual topic markers are used with different types of topics and in different contexts, and the topic markings cannot spread over other elements in the utterance.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topics can be moved from and remain null in the main clause of an utterance, or topics can be base-generated and either be co-referential to either the subject or object in the main clause or be related to the subject of object by a semantic property.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The first type of non-manual marking, topic marking 1 (tm1), is only used with a moved topic.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm1 is characterized by raised eyebrows, widened eyes, and head tilted backwards.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] At the end of the sign the head moves down and there is a pause, often with an eye blink, before the sentence is continued.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topic marking 2 (tm2) and topic marking 3 (tm3) are both used with base-generated topics.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm2 is characterized by raised eyebrows, widened eyes, and the head tilted backwards and to the side.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Toward the end of the sign the head moves forward and to the opposite side, and there is a pause and often an eye blink before continuing.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For tm3 the eyebrows are raised and the eyes are opened wide, the head starts tilted down and jerks up and down, the lips are opened and raised, and the head is nodded rapidly a few times before pausing and continuing the sentence.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Although both tm2 and tm3 accompany base-generated topics, they are used in different contexts.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm2 is used to introduce new information and change the topic of a conversation to something that the signer is going to subsequently characterize, while tm3 is used to introduce new information that the signer believes is already known by his/her interlocutor.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm2 may be used with any base-generated topic, whereas only topics that are co-referential with an argument in the sentence may be marked with tm3.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL sentences may have up to two marked topics.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Possible combinations of topic types are two tm2 topics, two tm3 topics, tm2 preceding tm1, tm3 preceding tm1, and tm2 preceding tm3.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Sentences with these topic combinations in the opposite orders or with two tm1 topics are considered ungrammatical by native signers.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Relative clauses are signaled by tilting back the head and raising the eyebrows and upper lip.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is done during the performance of the entire clause.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] where the brackets here indicate the duration of the non-manual features.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the sign 'recently' were made without these features, it would lie outside the relative clause, and the meaning would change to "the dog which chased the cat recently came home".
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Negated clauses may be signaled by shaking the head during the entire clause.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] A topic, however, cannot be so negated; the headshake can only be produced during the production of the main clause.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In addition, in many communities, negation is put at the end of the clause, unless there is a wh- question word.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the sentence, "I thought the movie was not good," could be signed as, "BEFORE MOVIE ME SEE, THINK WHAT?
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are two manual signs that negate a sentence, NOT and NONE, which are accompanied by a shake of the head.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are three types of questions with different constructions in ASL: wh- questions, yes/no questions, and rhetorical questions.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings are grammatical and semantic features that do not include the use of hands.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They can include mouth shape, eye gazes, facial expressions, body shifting, head tilting, and eyebrow raising.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings can also aid in identifying sentence type, which is especially relevant to our discussion of different types of interrogatives.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Wh-questions can be formed in a variety of ways in ASL.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The wh-word can appear solely at the end of the sentence, solely at the beginning of the sentence, at both the beginning and end of the sentence (see section 4.4.2.1 on 'double-occurring wh-words', or in situ (i.e. where the wh-word is in the sentence structure before movement occurs)).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Manual wh-signs are also accompanied by a non-manual grammatical marking (see section 4.4.1), which can include a variety of features.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This non-manual grammatical marking can spread optionally over the entire wh-phrase or just a small part.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some languages have very few wh-words, where context and discourse are sufficient to elicit the information that one needs.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL has many different wh-words, with certain wh-words having multiple variations.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] A list of the wh-words of ASL can be found below.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] As mentioned above, ASL possesses wh-questions with word initial placement, word final placement, in situ structure, but the most unique style of wh-word occurrence in ASL is where the wh-word occurs twice, copied in final position.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This doubling can be seen in the table below.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This doubling provides a useful template to analyze two separate analyses about whether wh-words move rightward or leftward in ASL.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] While some researchers argue for rightward movement in wh- questions such as Aarons and Neidle, others, including Petronio and Lillo-Martin, have argued that ASL has leftward movement and wh- words that appear to the right of the clause move by other processes.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Both analyses agree upon the fact that there is wh-movement present in these interrogative phrases, but it is a matter of what direction the wh-movement is moving in that causes controversy.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The leftward movement analysis is congruent with cross-linguistic data that wh-movement is always leftward.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It can be seen as the less controversial of the two proposals.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The main arguments presented by the Leftward Wh-movement analysis are: That the spec-CP is on the left, that the wh-movement is leftward, and that the final wh-word in a sentence is a base-generated double.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is illustrated in the syntax tree located to the right of this paragraph.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Arguments for leftward movement are based on the facts that if wh-movement in ASL were rightward, ASL would be an exception to cross-linguistic generalizations that wh-movement is leftward.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It has also been hypothesized that wh-elements cannot be topicalized, as topicalized elements must be presupposed and interrogatives are not.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This would be detrimental to the rightward analysis, as they are analyzing the doubled wh-word as a 'base generated topic'.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The rightward movement analysis is a newer, more abstract argument of how wh-movement occurs in ASL.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The main arguments for rightward movement begin by analyzing spec-CP as being on the right, the wh-movement as being rightward, and as the initial wh-word as a base-generated topic.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This can be seen in the syntax tree on the right.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] One of the rightward movement analysis' main arguments is in regards to the non-manual grammatical markings, and their optional spreading over the sentence.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL the use of non-manual grammatical markings is optional depending on the type of wh-question being asked.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In the rightward analysis both partial and full spreading of non-manual grammatical markers can be accounted for due to the association with the +WH feature over its c-command domain.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In the leftward analysis, the partial or full spreading of non manual grammatical markings cannot be accounted for in this same way.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The leftward movement analysis requires wh-marking to extend over the entirety of the question, regardless (which is not what is attested in ASL).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In spoken language Yes/no questions will oftentimes differ in their word order from the statement form.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL, yes/no questions are marked by the non-manual grammatical markings (as discussed in section 4.4.1).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This eyebrow raise, slight tilt of the head and lean forward are what indicate that a yes/no question is being asked, without any change in word order from the statement form.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There is speculation amongst linguists that these non-manual grammatical markings that indicate a yes/no questions are similar to the question intonation of spoken languages.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Yes/no questions differ from wh-questions as they do not differ in word order from the original statement form of the sentence, whereas wh-questions do.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] As well, in yes/no questions, the non-manual marking must be used over the whole utterance in order for it to be judged as a statement opposed to a question.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The yes/no question is the same word order as the statement form of the sentence, with the addition of non-manual grammatical markings.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings are also used for rhetorical questions, which are questions that do not intend to elicit an answer.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] To distinguish the non-manual marking for rhetorical questions from that of yes/no questions, the body is in a neutral position opposed to tilted forward, and the head is tilted in a different way than in yes/no questions.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Rhetorical questions are much more common in ASL than in English.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] [I LIKE]NEGATIVE [WHAT?]RHETORICAL, GARLIC.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This strategy is commonly used instead of signing the word 'because' for clarity or emphasis.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] PASTA I EAT ENJOY TRUE [WHY?]RHETORICAL, ITALIAN I.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL signers set up regions of space (loci) for specific referents (see above); these can then be referred to indexically by pointing at those locations with pronouns and indexical verbs.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] That is, they point to their referent, or to a locus representing their referent.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the referent is not physically present, the speaker identifies the referent and then points to a location (the *locus)* in the sign space near their body.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This locus can then be pointed at to refer to the referent.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Theoretically, any number of loci may be set up, as long as the signer and recipient remember them all, but in practice, no more than eight loci are used.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Meier 1990 demonstrates that only two grammatical persons are distinguished in ASL: First person and non-first person, as in Damin.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Both persons come in several numbers as well as with signs such as 'my' and 'by myself'.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Meier provides several arguments for believing that ASL does not formally distinguish second from third person.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, when pointing to a person that is physically present, a pronoun is equivalent to either 'you' or '(s)he' depending on the discourse.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There is nothing in the sign itself, nor in the direction of eye gaze or body posture, that can be relied on to make this distinction.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] That is, the same formal sign can refer to any of several second or third persons, which the indexic nature of the pronoun makes clear.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In English, indexic uses also occur, as in 'I need *you* to go to the store and *you* to stay here', but not so ubiquitously.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In contrast, several first-person ASL pronouns, such as the plural possessive ('our'), look different from their non-first-person equivalents, and a couple of pronouns do not occur in the first person at all, so first and non-first persons are formally distinct.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Personal pronouns have separate forms for singular ('I' and 'you/(s)he') and plural ('we' and 'you/they').
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These have possessive counterparts: 'my', 'our', 'your/his/her', 'your/their'.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In addition, there are pronoun forms which incorporate numerals from two to five ('the three of us', 'the four of you/them', etc.), though the dual pronouns are slightly idiosyncratic in form *(i.e.,* they have a K rather than 2 handshape, and the wrist nods rather than circles).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These numeral-incorporated pronouns have no possessive equivalents.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Also among the personal pronouns are the 'self' forms ('by myself', 'by your/themselves', etc.).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These only occur in the singular and plural (there is no numeral incorporation), and are only found as subjects.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They have derived emphatic and 'characterizing' forms, with modifications used for derivation rather like those for verbal aspect.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The 'characterizing' pronoun is used when describing someone who has just been mentioned.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It only occurs as a non-first-person singular form.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Finally, there are formal pronouns used for honored guests.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These occur as singular and plural in the non-first person, but only as singular in the first person.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL is a pro-drop language, which means that pronouns are not used when the referent is obvious from context and is not being emphasized.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Within ASL there is a class of indexical (often called 'directional') verbs.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These include the signs for 'see', 'pay', 'give', 'show', 'invite', 'help', 'send', 'bite', etc.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These verbs include an element of motion that indexes one or more referents, either physically present or set up through the referent locus system.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If there are two loci, the first indicates the subject and the second the object, direct or indirect depending on the verb, reflecting the basic word order of ASL.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, 'give' is a bi-indexical verb based on a flattened M/O handshape.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For 'I give you', the hand moves from myself toward you; for 'you give me', it moves from you to me.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The verb 'to be in pain' (index fingers pointed at each other and alternately approaching and separating) is signed at the location of the pain (head for headache, cheek for toothache, abdomen for stomachache, etc.).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is normally done in relation to the signer's own body, regardless of the person feeling the pain, but may take also use the locus system, especially for body parts which are not normally part of the sign space, such as the leg.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are also spatial verbs such as put-up and put-below, which allow signers to specify where things are or how they moved them around.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-phabet] Like SignFont and Stokoe notation, ASL-phabet is a phonemic script, but it has been simplified to the point where there is some ambiguity, that is, one symbol can represent more than one phonemic element (handshape, location or movement).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-phabet] For example, whereas SignFont has 25 letters encoding types of movement, and Stokoe notation has 24, ASL-phabet has just 5.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-phabet] This can result in homographs (more than one sign spelled the same way).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-phabet] All together, ASL-phabet has 22 letters for handshape, 5 for location, and 5 for movement.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-phabet] They are written in that order, left-to-right, with the possibility for several letters of each type, such as two handshape letters for a two-handed sign.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-phabet] Like Stokoe notation (but unlike SignFont), the ASL-phabet does not provide symbols for facial expressions, mouthing, and other aspects of sign language structure, which may make it hard to use for extended text.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/asl-phabet] However, it is sufficient to look up ASL words in an ASL–English dictionary.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] Its core components are digits, locatives, marks and movements which are written in a fairly rigid order (though in a fairly flexible configuration) from left to right.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] The order of the writing is from left to right, top to bottom, with locatives or certain marks often beginning words.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] Sentences are ended by the full stop mark ().
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] Questions in written ASL are denoted by eyebrow marks bounding the question not unlike Spanish's "¿ ?." Question words or wh-questions in ASL can also form the interrogative.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] There are in total 105 characters in ASLwrite with 67 digits, five diacritic marks, twelve locatives, sixteen extramanual marks and five movement marks.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] Since its creation, it has evolved to include more digits, locatives, movements and marks as well as modify those already present.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] si5s, a system built from SignWriting, was first proposed by Robert Arnold in his 2007 Gallaudet thesis *A Proposal of the Written System for ASL*.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] The ASLwrite community split from Arnold upon his decision to maintain si5s as a private venture with ASLized after the publication of his and Adrean Clark's book *How to Write American Sign Language*.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] Aside from the small, but dedicated, Facebook group of around 470 in July 2023, ASLwrite is rarely used outside such online spaces.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] However, one of the most popular online ASL dictionaries, HandSpeak, has begun to incorporate ASLwrite as the primary written component of ASL definitions.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] ASLwrite is a somacheirographic system meaning that it represents the body (Greek: σῶμα *sôma* 'body') and hands (Greek: χείρ *kheír* 'hand') and relays phonemic information.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] However, it also incorporates logographs (questioning marks) and is featural.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] The general principle is to capture a single ASL word per segment, from left to right, registering non-manual feature(s), location(s), handshape(s), movement(s) and general orientation.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] It imagines the writer/speaker is looking down at their hands or viewing words from the profile such that words can be made either as if seen from straight-on or from one's profile.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] The digibet captures handshape information as well as orientation, movement and some locations.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] Locatives are characters that capture location, though handshape diacritics like *edge* do capture some locations such as edge of palm.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] Diacritics, such as movements, modify handshapes and can indicate small movements or small orientations.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] Movements themselves are fairly flexible in their shapes and orientations, which makes digitising this script difficult.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] Frontal or profile locatives – Captures the same location information, just from two perspectives.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] An example (seen on the right) is the shoulder locative is either a shoulder frontal locative that is written above or below the handshape(s).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] Handshapes – Can be written before or after the locative.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] A handshape can be oriented in 360° depending on its location and is written at the end of its movement path if there is one.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] Each handshape present is written, and when more than one handshape (of one hand) is written, a movement must be present.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] Movements – Larger movements or movements that affect multiple handshapes.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] When a handshape changes without overt movement, the handshapes are written left-to-right with a single movement below, similar to an underline.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] Non-manual & punctuation marks – These are questioning marks such as *why*, *who*, *how* and *how*.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] The digibet is composed of handshapes called digits that are modified by diacritics and movements.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] It shares 23 handshapes with ASL's manual alphabet.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] Digits are grouped together by features such as +thumb/-thumb or +closed/-closed.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] In practise, there are 67 digits in ASLwrite's digibet, though that number is growing as new digits are added representing diverse handshapes.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] Moreover, other languages may adopt this system which would add increasingly more digits.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] There are five diacritics, of which one is a movement diacritic.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] Movements are flexible and thus hard to capture in a digital or non-handwritten fashion.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] The movements are diverse and aim to capture the movements of the hands, arms and body.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] There are three points – an **endpoint**, a **firmpoint** and a **contactpoint** –, an **orbit mark**, a **steering** and a **crank mark** as well as the movement mark or line.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] The movement line follows the path of the hand(s) and can be as clean (e.g., – or | ) or as erratic as possible.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] The points denote the end of a handshape's path and the degree to which the motion is made.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] A contactpoint denotes an imaginary or in-the-air point with the contactpoint ending at a location and noted as being a firm ending with the firmpoint.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] The orbit mark indicates a central "point" around which the handshapes orbit; for orbital paths cut short, one would use a steering mark, and for parallel cranking motions, the crank mark would be used.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] The locatives are characters that denote a specific location on or near the signer's body.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] They are presented from a face-on and side-view.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] The two sub-classifications are **frontal** and **profile locatives**.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] Non-manual marks vary quite significantly and can only be placed at the beginning or end of words or phrases.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] **Eyebrow marks** are denoted before and after the word(s) in question thus bounding the words that are modified by eyebrow marks.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] They are called: **Raised (), Knit, Wan, Slanted** and **Squint**.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] Questioning marks exist in ASL as logographs that denote ASL's wh-questions such as WHO or FOR-FOR.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] They are placed after a closed word's or phrase's second eyebrow mark and can exist as an entire sentence alone.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] Mouth marks are characters that relay what action the mouth is doing.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] It is placed inside the first eyebrow mark.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] Body movements are non-manual, non-facial features such as **shoulder shift ()** or **head nod**.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] They, as well as **nose crinkle ()**, stand alone and can be inserted anywhere, inside and outside of eyebrow-marked phrases.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] means *Yes?* in ASL composed of , , and where the raised eyebrow marks at the beginning and the end indicate it is a yes/no question, and the hinge mark () denotes that the S handshape digit () makes a nodding motion.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] The circular point at the end is a full stop mark indicating the end of the sentence.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] Unlike in English writing, the full stop mark () is employed for all sentences, even questions (as seen here).
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] Breaks in the sentence, as seen below, are denoted by the shoulder shift mark ().
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] The text on the right is from Chapters 1:2–4 of the Book of Ruth.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] The first quoted text is the verse in English and the second is an ASL gloss.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] Due to the complexity of the writing system and its need for flexibility for movements, it means that producing anything in a digital format is difficult.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] However, there are efforts to create fonts headed by members of its Facebook group, notably looking at proper font creation and using current keyboard characters such as ' } ' or ' _.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] ' to achieve minor forms of communication in ASL over text.
[src:adamorobe-sign-language/aslwrite] An example phrase is " }_.U- " which means 'thank you' in ASL.
